	"notes": [
		{
			"id": "nY9br6sqPB5M69hjj",
			"markdown": "The Roughneck survives through grit, labor, endurance, and practical skill. Whether you are a miner hacking tunnels through an asteroid, a frontier homesteader raising crops on a hostile colony world, a scavenger rebuilding civilization from scrap, a long-haul trucker hauling freight through radioactive badlands, or an overworked utility technician keeping a cyberpunk megacity’s failing infrastructure alive, you solve problems through experience and hard work rather than education or prestige. When conditions become harsh, supplies run short, equipment breaks down, or civilized people realize they are far from comfort and safety, the Roughneck becomes indispensable.\n\nRoughnecks thrive in dangerous and unforgiving environments where comfort, infrastructure, and support cannot be taken for granted. They are laborers, builders, settlers, prospectors, mechanics, hunters, cargo crews, and survivalists accustomed to solving practical problems with whatever tools happen to be available. In many campaigns, Roughnecks are the backbone of colonies, expeditions, mining operations, caravans, salvage crews, frontier towns, industrial projects, and urban infrastructure. They know how to build shelter, repair equipment, move cargo, endure hardship, and keep functioning long after others have given up.\n\nThe *Colonist* builds civilization where none exists. Homesteaders, terraformers, agricultural crews, settlement founders, frontier families, and construction workers all belong to this archetype. Colonists specialize in creating food, shelter, infrastructure, and long-term stability in hostile environments where survival depends on cooperation and practical knowledge. They emphasize Farming, Carpentry, Masonry, Electrician, Animal Handling, Gardening, Survival, Area Knowledge, Green Thumb, Master Builder, Animal Empathy, Common Sense, and Fit. This archetype excels in colony campaigns, wilderness frontiers, reconstruction efforts, and survival-focused games where communities must be built and maintained. Colonists often develop strong obligations to their homes and communities, making disadvantages such as Charitable, Sense of Duty, Workaholic, Stubbornness, Truthfulness, Poor, or Social Stigma (Uneducated) especially appropriate.\n\nThe *Bushwhacker* survives where maps fail and civilization ends. Hunters, trappers, prospectors, wilderness guides, scavengers, bush pilots, and frontier drifters all fit this archetype. Bushwhackers specialize in self-reliance, mobility, and surviving in dangerous territory far from support or infrastructure. They emphasize Survival, Tracking, Fishing, Prospecting, Navigation, Stealth, Hiking, Guns, Outdoorsman, Danger Sense, Absolute Direction, Fearlessness, and Intuition. This archetype thrives in wilderness campaigns, hostile colony worlds, gritty survival games, and long-range expeditions into unexplored territory. Life on the edge of civilization often leaves Bushwhackers isolated, suspicious, or fiercely independent, making disadvantages such as Loner, Curious, Xenophobia, Miserliness, Overconfidence, Hidebound, or Odious Personal Habit common choices.\n\nThe *Industrial Worker* keeps civilization functioning through dangerous labor, endurance, and technical experience. Miners, refinery crews, cargo handlers, heavy-equipment operators, oil-riggers, demolition teams, tunnel engineers, utility workers, and hazardous-environment laborers all belong to this archetype. Industrial Workers specialize in operating dangerous machinery, enduring brutal conditions, and solving practical problems through experience instead of theory. They emphasize Mechanic, Freight Handling, Hazardous Materials, Engineer (Mining), Driving, Prospecting, Electronics Repair, Survival, Fit, High Pain Threshold, Common Sense, Fearlessness, and Gizmo. This archetype excels in industrial campaigns, extraction economies, hazardous work zones, frontier colonies, disaster-response scenarios, and cyberpunk settings where aging infrastructure barely functions and corporations treat workers as disposable. Industrial Workers can easily become asteroid miners, orbital dockworkers, refinery crews, salvage operators, or EVA laborers by adding skills such as Spacer, Vacc Suit, and Free Fall, along with advantages like Born Spacer, G-Experience, or Resistant. Years of exhausting labor, dangerous environments, and economic instability often produce disadvantages such as Alcoholism, Workaholic, Greed, Compulsive Gambling, Chummy, Code of Honor (Professional), Bad Reputation, or Sense of Duty.\n\nThe *Scavenger* survives by reclaiming what others leave behind. Scrap dealers, junkers, rogue mechanics, collapse survivors, black-market salvagers, wasteland traders, and improvised repair crews all belong to this archetype. Scavengers specialize in improvisation, repair, opportunism, and turning broken equipment into usable tools. They emphasize Scrounging, Mechanic, Smith, Merchant, Freight Handling, Urban Survival, Stealth, Electronics Repair, Gizmo, Serendipity, Luck, Artificer, and Intuition. This archetype thrives in gritty campaigns with decaying industrial worlds, underfunded colonies, salvage economies, and warzones where resources are scarce and nothing goes to waste. Because survival often depends on opportunism and bending the rules, Scavengers commonly develop disadvantages such as Greed, Selfish, Trickster, Miserliness, Compulsive Spending, Social Stigma, or Unluckiness.\n\nAn important choice for any Roughneck is deciding whether they are primarily builders, survivors, laborers, or opportunists. Some Roughnecks focus on community and infrastructure, becoming invaluable settlers and engineers who hold civilization together through hard work and cooperation. Others become fiercely independent wanderers, scavengers, or survivalists who trust their instincts more than institutions. Many balance practical labor skill with wilderness expertise, technical knowledge, or combat ability depending on the dangers of the setting.\n\nRoughnecks also benefit enormously from campaign-specific specialization. In frontier games, Survival, Animal Handling, Tracking, Prospecting, and Farming may define the character. In industrial or cyberpunk settings, Mechanic, Electronics Repair, Freight Handling, and Hazardous Materials become increasingly important. In space campaigns, Spacer, Vacc Suit, Free Fall, and Piloting can transform a Roughneck into a void-worker, asteroid miner, or salvage operator. Whatever form they take, Roughnecks excel at keeping people alive, equipment functioning, and civilization operating under the harshest possible conditions."
		}
	]
}
